The paper deals with algorithms for maintaining shortest paths in graphs, which is a fundamental problem in computer science. The focus is on partially dynamic algorithms, which suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The use of hubs and the improvement of randomized algorithms also suggest that the paper could belong to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-categories. The use of approximation algorithms and the analysis of running time suggest that the paper could also belong to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category. Finally, the use of Las Vegas randomized algorithms suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
